=== Early years ===

Skinner represented [[Saint Andrew's School, Singapore|Saint Andrew's School]] in [[association football|football]], [[field hockey|hockey]] and [[cricket]].<ref name=interview62>{{cite news|last1=Kraal|first1=David|title=Skinner - two games for Singapore|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19620325-1.2.138|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=25 March 1962|p=22}}</ref> He grew up near the beach in Kakikal Lane, [[Katong]] and would practise diving after imaginary balls on the beach in the mornings and evenings.<ref name=kraal>{{cite news|last1=Kraal|first1=David|title=Skinner <U+2013> Singapore's greatest goalkeeper|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19991010-1.2.74.1|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=10 October 1999|p=54}}</ref> He played bare-footed for Katong Boys' Club which won the 1950 Singapore Boys' Football Cup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Katong Boys In Semi-final|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19500724-1.2.144|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=24 July 1950|p=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Katong regains Boys soccer title|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page.aspx?pageid=freepress19500823-1.1.11|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=23 August 1950|p=11}}</ref> The Cup win earned Skinner a pair of boots and a place in Saint Andrew's second football team, where he played as a right winger.<ref name=kraal/> He had to play in goal after the team's goalkeeper did not turn up for a match, and his performance earned him promotion to the first team after only two games with the second team.<ref name=kraal/><ref>{{cite news|title=A goalkeeper by chance|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19520317-1.2.134|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=17 March 1952|p=11}}</ref> He also represented the Combined Schools team for five years under honorary coach [[Choo Seng Quee]].<ref name=interview62/><ref>{{cite news|title=Trial School XI win 4-0|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19500324-1.2.170|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=24 March 1950|p=12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Koh|first1=Peng Long|title=S'pore schoolboys out for revenge|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=freepress19500427-1.2.115|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=27 April 1950|p=7}}</ref><ref name=interview88>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=A Singapore legend takes trip down Memory Lane|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page.aspx?pageid=straitstimes19880306-1.1.24|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=6 March 1988|p=24}}</ref> He was awarded Combined Schools Colours in 1952, 1953 and 1954.<ref>{{cite news|title=Colony's top 17 schools sports stars selected|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19521204-1.2.192|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 December 1952|p=12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 receive colours|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530314-1.2.187|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 March 1953|p=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Schools stars honoured|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19540324-1.2.203|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=24 March 1954|p=14}}</ref>

=== Club ===

Skinner joined Rovers Sports Club's newly formed junior team in 1951.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rovers go to schools for new talent|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19510614-1.2.173|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 June 1951|p=12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Juniors are Cup men in the making|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19510615-1.2.160|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=15 June 1951|p=12}}</ref> A year later, he played for Rovers 'A', the second team, which ended runners-up in the 1952 [[Singapore Amateur Football Association|SAFA]] Third Division.<ref>{{cite news|title=S.A.F.A. forgot to promote Rovers 'A'|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530310-1.2.148|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=10 March 1953|p=12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Div. 3 soccer in three sections this season|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530114-1.2.156|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 January 1953|p=12}}</ref> On 2 May 1953, Skinner made his senior debut for Rovers in a 3<U+2013>0 win over Pulau Brani United in the First Division.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wilf Skinner shines in Rovers 3-0 win|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530503-1.2.153|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 May 1953|p=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wonderful, say the Aussie boys|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530505-1.2.185|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=5 May 1953|p=12}}</ref> Rovers finished as 1953 First Division runners-up and 1954 SAFA Challenge Cup winners<ref name=ccup54>{{cite news|title=Rovers are Cup champions...|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19541113-1.2.170|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=13 November 1954|p=14}}</ref>

In December 1954, Skinner joined the [[Singapore Police Force|Police Force]] and played for [[Home United FC|Police Sports Association]] after leaving school.<ref name=interview62/><ref>{{cite news|title=Skinner to miss HK - career first|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19541118-1.2.160|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=18 November 1954|p=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer begins with Police<U+2013>C.A. game|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19550304-1.2.230|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 March 1955|p=14}}</ref> He was also utilised in a centre or wide [[Forward (association football)|forward]] role throughout his playing career with Police.<ref>{{cite news|title=When thousands flocked to watch matches in an 86-team League|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19910303-1.2.34.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 March 1991|p=26}}</ref><ref name=seh/> Skinner won the inaugural President's Cup under coach [[Choo Seng Quee]] in January 1969.<ref>{{cite news|title=President's Trophy match in S'pore now|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19690103-1.2.116.8|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 January 1969|p=19}}</ref><ref name=pcup1969>{{cite news|title=President's Cup goes to Police|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19690112-1.2.128|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=12 January 1969|p=20}}</ref>

Skinner also represented the [[Singapore Lions|Singapore state team]] which participated in Malayan competitions including the [[Malaya Cup]]. On 26 June 1960, Skinner received an ovation from the 12,350-strong [[Jalan Besar Stadium|Jalan Besar]] crowd for his role in Singapore's 2<U+2013>1 victory over Malaya Cup holders [[Selangor FA|Selangor]]; he considered this win to be his most memorable match in a 1988 interview.<ref name=interview88/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Skinner stops Selangor|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19600627-1.2.82|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=27 June 1960|p=11}}</ref> Singapore went on to lift the Cup that year.<ref name=mcup60>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Malaya Cup to Singapore|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19600918-1.2.112|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=18 September 1960|p=20}}</ref>
In November 1960, [[Singapore Amateur Football Association|SAFA]] president Soh Ghee Soon confirmed that Skinner "requested" his withdrawal from the Singapore team that would tour Hong Kong and Saigon as he could not train with the team due to his hockey commitments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skinner withdraws from tour side|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19601105-1.2.137|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=5 November 1960|p=17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=SAFA won't make overtures to Rahim Omar|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19601111-1.2.139|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=11 November 1960|p=15}}</ref> Skinner quit the Malaya Cup team after he alleged he was unfairly dropped by Soh.<ref>{{cite news|author=B. Norman|title=Soh wanted to drop me from the tour team, says Skinner|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=freepress19601109-1.2.91|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=9 November 1960|p=10}}</ref> He resolved his differences with the SAFA and rejoined the team in late December.<ref>{{cite news|title=SAFA and 'rebels' make peace|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19601228-1.2.117|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=28 December 1960|p=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Jeffrey|title=Three soccer stars make Christmas visit to Soh|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=freepress19601228-1.2.158|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=28 December 1960|p=14}}</ref> Skinner missed the following season after he left for a four-month training at the Detectives' Training School in Calcutta under a [[Colombo Plan]] scholarship in March 1961.<ref name=india>{{cite news|title=Off to India, Wilf says: It will help my hockey|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19610310-1.2.134|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=10 March 1961|p=15}}</ref> Singapore won the [[FAM Cup]] in 1963 but Skinner did not play in the final. He featured in both finals as Singapore won the Malaya Cup in 1964 and 1965.<ref name=mcup64>{{cite news|last1=Pidgeon|first1=Bob|title=90-minute Malaya Cup thriller|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19640809-1.2.135.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=9 August 1964|p=14}}</ref><ref name=mcup65>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Singapore's Cup again|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19650801-1.2.41.21|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=1 August 1965|p=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Skinner's 'wonder' saves stand out as gems in sparkling cup final|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19650802-1.2.134.10|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=2 August 1965|p=22}}</ref> Following the 1965 Cup win, he announced his intention to step down from the state team but retracted his decision and was included in the 1966 squad.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=Four S'pore stars call it a day|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page.aspx?pageid=straitstimes19650803-1.1.20|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 August 1965|p=20}}</ref> He played in the earlier rounds of the 1967 FAM Cup, which Singapore won, but missed the final due to a neck injury sustained during the [[1968 AFC Asian Cup qualification|Asian Cup qualifiers]] in March.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=Singapore qualify for final|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670313-1.2.111|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=13 March 1967|p=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=Cup double for first time is S'pore target|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670411-1.2.120|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=11 April 1967|p=17}}</ref> The FAM Cup was Skinner's last involvement with the state team as he was dropped from the 1967 [[Malaysia Cup]] (the renamed Malaya Cup) squad with the form of replacement [[Ahmad Wartam]], and the [[Football Association of Singapore]] withdrew the team from Malaysia competitions in 1968 and 1969.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dali Omar dropped by Armed Forces|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670420-1.2.120|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=20 April 1967|p=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Siebel|first=Norman|title=Break sad but not surprising|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19680517-1.2.157.4|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=17 May 1968|p=22}}</ref>

=== International ===

In 1953, Skinner was called up to the Singapore team in place of first-choice goalkeeper [[Chu Chee Seng]]. He made his international debut against Malaya in the annual Sportsmen's Trophy on 13 September.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore drop Bakar, Chee Seng|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530908-1.2.169|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=8 September 1953|p=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Federation field four subs and win|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19530914-1.2.166|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 September 1953|p=12}}</ref> Skinner also represented Singapore at the [[Football at the 1954 Asian Games|1954 Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite news|title=These boys want to give up football|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19540821-1.2.171|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=21 August 1954|p=13}}</ref> On 4 April 1962, he captained Singapore for the first time in a match against Peruvian club [[Sporting Cristal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Skinner leads Spore|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19620402-1.2.102.7|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=2 April 1962|p=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=All-S'pore make Peruvians struggle for goals|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19620429-1.2.123|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=29 April 1962|p=20}}</ref>

With the impending merger of Singapore, Malaya, British North Borneo and Sarawak to form Malaysia, Skinner was included in the 18-man Malaysian squad for the [[Merdeka Tournament]] in August 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six S'pore players in Malaysia squad|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19630731-1.2.133|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=31 July 1963|p=20}}</ref> He made his debut for Malaysia in a 5<U+2013>0 loss to South Vietnam on 12 August.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Slow, struggling Malaysia|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19630812-1.2.113|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=12 August 1963|p=18}}</ref> Four days later, he skippered the team in place of injured captain Abdul Gani as hosts Malaysia defeated South Korea 3<U+2013>0.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Malaysia first to humble mighty Koreans|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19630817-1.2.138|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=17 August 1963|p=20}}</ref> Skinner also featured for Malaysia in the 1964 Merdeka Tournament.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gabrielle to miss first game v Thais|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19640820-1.2.123.4|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=20 August 1964|p=17}}</ref>

In December 1965, Skinner represented the newly-independent nation of Singapore at the [[Football at the 1965 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games|1965 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|last2=Frida|first2=Ernest|title=S'pore bank on Malaya Cup winning team|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19651105-1.2.120.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=5 November 1965|p=23}}</ref> He was selected in the Singapore squad for the 1966 Merdeka Tournament.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore name 17 for Merdeka Tournament|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19660805-1.2.146.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=5 August 1966|p=19}}</ref> Skinner's last international assignment was the [[1968 AFC Asian Cup qualification|1968 Asian Cup qualification]] in Hong Kong in March 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incentive award from today|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670312-1.2.55.12|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=12 March 1967|p=18}}</ref> In September, national coach [[Choo Seng Quee]]'s request to recall Skinner for the up-coming [[Football at the 1967 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games|Southeast Asian Peninsular Games]] was rejected by the [[Football Association of Singapore]] and he was not included in the shortlist of players.<ref>{{cite news|title=Choo wants Skinner back in Games squad|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670905-1.2.135.6|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=5 September 1967|p=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=32 in Singapore squad|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19670914-1.2.135.1|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 September 1967|p=23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=Nine dropped from Seap Games training squad|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19671004-1.2.122.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 October 1967|p=19}}</ref> The FAS decision eventually proved irrelevant as the football team dropped from the Games contingent by the [[Sport Singapore|National Sports Council Board]] in November.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frida|first1=Ernest|title=S'pore axe four for Seap|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19671103-1.2.109.3|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 November 1967|p=21}}</ref>

{{Cquote|(Skinner) was the most impressive I have seen up to this stage of the tour. He robbed us of at least four more certain goals. I will not hesitate to say that he is good enough for any leading English First Division side. No matter where he plays, whether in Manchester or Liverpool, he is going to stand between the same posts as in Singapore. If as an amateur he could show such good potentialities, he will be even better as a professional.<br>{{align|right|<U+2013> [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] manager, [[Vic Buckingham]], June 1966<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dorai|first1=Joe|title=Skinner good for English Div 1 - Vic|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19660606-1.2.123|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=6 June 1966|p=19}}</ref>}}}}

Skinner is widely considered as one of the best goalkeepers to play for Singapore.<ref name=kraal/><ref name=seh>{{cite news|last1=Seh|first1=Jerry|title=Seh: Legendary Chu is my all-time great|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19970225-1.2.46.4|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=25 February 1997|p=31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Robert|first1=Godfrey|title=These Lions are World-Cup class|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19991114-1.1.52.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 November 1999|p=52}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nair|first1=Suresh|title=When goalies were stars|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=newpaper20010610-1.2.57.7|newspaper=[[The New Paper]]|date=10 June 2001|p=51}}</ref> He was ranked 32nd in a list of ''Singapore's 50 Greatest Athletes of the Century'' by ''[[The Straits Times]]'' in 1999 and was the only goalkeeper in the list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Here's the full list|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19991219-1.2.64.5.3|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=19 December 1999|p=52}}</ref>

