=== Club ===

Skinner joined Police Sports Association's hockey team when he entered the [[Singapore Police Force|Police Force]] in December 1954.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marks|first1=John|title=New men just right for Police hockey|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19541104-1.2.202|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 November 1954|p=14}}</ref> He played alongside [[Percy Pennefather]], captain of Police SA and the national hockey team at the [[Field hockey at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Olympic Games]], and national football team captain [[Lee Kok Seng]]. Police reached their first Oehlers Cup final, Singapore Hockey Association's senior knockout tournament, in 1956 but lost 3<U+2013>2 to University of Malaya.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police and Varsity meet in senior K.O. final today|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19560228-1.2.152|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=28 February 1956|p=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ang|first1=Kam Hock|title=Inspired Varsity set the pace|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19560229-1.2.169|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=29 February 1956|p=14}}</ref> On 1 March 1957, Police defeated holders University of Malaya 2<U+2013>0 in the semi-final of the Oehlers Cup after three replays.<ref>{{cite news|title=The hockey marathon is over: Police for final|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19570302-1.2.154|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=2 March 1957|p=13}}</ref> Five days later, Police claimed their first trophy with a 2<U+2013>0 victory over Singapore Recreation Club "Reds" in the final.<ref name=oc57>{{cite news|title=Police deserved cup - but not on yesterday's form|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=freepress19570307-1.2.82|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=7 March 1957|p=15}}</ref> Skinner also won the SHA Division One title with Police in 1958.<ref name=sha58>{{cite news|title=Police take league title with three Pennefather goals|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19581214-1.2.147|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=14 December 1958|p=27}}</ref>

=== International ===

In October 1959, right-half Skinner received his first call-up to the Singapore state hockey team for the Malaya Hockey Federation (MHF) inter-state quadrangular.<ref>{{cite news|title=SHA pick four newcomers for 'Quad'|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19591019-1.2.106|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=19 October 1959|p=15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quad title to S'pore - defenders in top form|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19591026-1.2.90|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=26 October 1959|p=12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=A busy day for Frida and Wilf - and so important too|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19591115-1.2.101|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=15 November 1959|p=23}}</ref> He made his international debut in a 2<U+2013>0 win over Malaya on 28 November 1959.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Teoh|first1=Eng Tatt|title=SHA hopes to reap harvest|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19591128-1.2.119|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=28 November 1959|p=17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=F. Salahudin|title=Singapore gain first international win|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19591129-1.2.122|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=29 November 1959|p=23}}</ref> By the early 1960s, Skinner established himself as Singapore's regular centre-half and skipper.<ref name=interview62/><ref name=india/><ref>{{cite news|title=Vote now to elect Singapore champ for 1961|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=freepress19611222-1.2.106|newspaper=The Singapore Free Press|date=22 December 1961|p=14}}</ref><ref name=quitpolice/> He captained Singapore at the [[Field hockey at the 1962 Asian Games|1962 Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SHA name 16 players for the A-Games|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19620801-1.2.141.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=1 August 1962|p=19}}</ref>

In October 1961, the MHF approved Singapore's return to the Pan-Malayan inter-state championship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Players welcome choice of Coutts|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19611031-1.2.152|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=31 October 1961|p=19}}</ref> Singapore lost 3<U+2013>0 to Selangor in the 1962 inter-state final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sabapathy's goal cracks Singapore after 42 minutes|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19621203-1.2.134|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=3 December 1962|p=20}}</ref> In 1963, the MHF inter-state competition underwent a change in format to a Cup competition and was renamed the [[Tun Abdul Razak|Razak]] Cup.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siebel|first1=Norman|title=Tournament for Razak Cup will boost hockey|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19620613-1.2.117.6|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=13 June 1962|p=19}}</ref> Skinner won the 1965 edition with Singapore.<ref name=rcup65>{{cite news|title=Singapore continue reign as Malaysian hockey champions|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page.aspx?pageid=straitstimes19650117-1.1.12|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=17 January 1965|p=12}}</ref>

== Personal life ==

Skinner joined the [[Singapore Police Force|Police Force]] after graduating from school in December 1954. He rose to the rank of [[Assistant Superintendent]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police PR Wong among 36 'new-style' officers promoted|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19710404-1.2.3|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 April 1971|p=1}}</ref> In August 1974, Skinner was awarded the bronze [[Pingat Pentadbiran Awam]] state medal.<ref name=ppa>{{cite news|title=National Day honours for 332|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19740809-1.1.7.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=9 August 1974|p=7}}</ref> After 20 years of service in the Police Force, Skinner resigned in late December 1974 and emigrated to Canada, where he worked as a handyman.<ref name=interview88/><ref name=quitpolice>{{cite news|title=Skinner quits Police Force|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19741228-1.2.63|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=28 December 1974|p=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A line from Skinner|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes19780309-1.2.110.2|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=9 March 1978|p=23}}</ref>

Skinner married wife Moira in 6 May 1967; they have a son, Judd James (born 1969).<ref name=kraal/><ref name=interview88/><ref>{{cite web|title=Wilfred J. SKINNER|url=http://www.geni.com/people/Wilfred-J-SKINNER/6000000002901226727|website=[[Geni.com]]|publisher=[[MyHeritage]]|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref>

== Death ==

Skinner died at the age of 69 in [[Vancouver]], Canada on 2 August 2003. He had been in a coma for two weeks after suffering a [[heart attack]].<ref name=kraal2>{{cite news|last1=Kraal|first1=David|title=Skinner the legend dies|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article.aspx?articleid=straitstimes20030804-1.2.45.16|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=4 August 2003|p=9}}</ref>

